Apothecia disk is maily flat, minor comlex bumpy or polydisc. Apothecia are sessile up to subpedicellate (in the guidebook only subpedicellate). There are light-brown bottom edges up to pinkish-white and dark brown centre. Close to the edge of the lichen there are rare brown outgrowths similar to the “scaly isidia” of guidebook L. rossica.
Description of L. rossica is rather detailed and has many variations, including much different forms with papillose surface, as example https://www.plantarium.ru/page/image/id/487020.html
So, “velvety” L. rossica looks similar to some Lasallia pustulata; “green and brown” form is similar to L. papulosa with “scaly-like isidia”; L. rossica with dark brown bottom surface is similar to some L. pensylvanica (dark brown bottom up to black).
I think that guide booke are more different than lichens.

results.notes: This fungus appears to have an affinity for charred wood and the surface layer of ash after a bush fire.  This was taken 2 weeks after fire had passed though.  The forest is Wet Sclerophyll (Eucalyptus canopy with rainforest species as an understory).  This forest burns infrequently, but without fire it would not exist (it would become rainforest).  When the fungus grows on the ash layer it holds the top layer of soil together and also protects the soil from drying out.  There was rain here last week, but most of it has dryed out on the surface, except where there is a layer of fungus. This fungus is very common now and holds together much of the top soil layer.

results.notes:
I’m new to mushrooms but am excited to learn about these fascinating organisms. I am not planning on ingesting any for some time.
It is early winter, late fall here in Kentucky. Temperatures are above freezing, and it’s been raining every few days. I was searching the forest behind my apartment building for mushrooms when I found quite a few species growing on dead deciduous trees (most fallen logs and branches).
However, I found a medium sized brown mushroom growing out of the forest floor that was covered in fallen leaves. Very hard to spot, but once I found the first the others started appearing among the fallen leaves. They did not seem to grow In clusters, more spread out, but a few were coupled at the base.
I’m not experienced in spore prints, but I cut off a cap and placed it spore side down onto computer paper over night. It deposited a white outline, with some brown towards the center. Wasn’t sure if the brown was from the moisture of the mushroom or if the white was from the crumpling of the paper, but it seems to be mostly white powdery deposits.
Could you please help me identify this mushroom?

results.notes:
I am new to mushroom identification. I have only identified beginner ones, Chanterelle, Oyster, Chicken, Bolete using Lincoff’s Mushroom Hunter and have started using David Aurora’s Mushrooms Demystified to identify a Lactarius. I am trying to now identify some past the “beginner” stage.

I found hundreds of these growing yesterday in Cincinnati on my urban hike, I tried to take up the challenge of identifying, but keep getting stuck! Hence asking for help here :)

It’s a white spored mushroom. I don’t think it’s Russulaceae because I didn’t notice any latex, nor did it snap like a chalk.

I’m stuck on either Hygrophoraceae or Tricholomatacea since I’ve never identified either. I don’t think it’s particularly waxy, but that seems so subjective I’m not sure! It’s smells very fragrant and is not bitter at all, tastes very good actually – spit it out of course – and rinsed my mouth!

It keyed out to Hygrophorus pudorinus (but I definitely don’t think it’s that).

With T, maybe it keyed out to Lyophllum?

Some older specimens were dark as well. Also, there was no volva, and the gills were adnate. With umbilicate to depressed cap at maturity.

This is my first time here, so thank you for your patience in advance!!
